post_text:
The middle school and high school yearbooks are in!

They will be distributed during GAP on Thursday.

For graduates and anyone else not in the building this year, you may pick up your copy in the main office during regular school hours.

Extras are available for purchase. Middle school books are $20 and high school books are $40. Drop off a check (to "New London Local Schools") at the board office and we will get you a book within 24 hours. Please include a phone number on the check if you do not have a student in the building.

Thank you for supporting the Yearbook staff and helping to make last school year so special.

Attention parents....Starting next week we are collecting select Chromebooks starting August 19, 2020. If your student belongs to any of the following groups, please drop off your chromebook outside the main entrance of the elementary from 8:00 am - 3:30pm:

-1st year EHOVE Student
-3rd grader for the 2020 SY
-8th grader for the 2020SY
-You've moved out of our district
-Any grade if your student's chromebook has significant
damage such as a cracked screen, missing keys, or won't
turn on.

Please place the chromebook in a bag and write your student's name and grade level on the outside of the bag.

This will allow our tech staff to repair any damaged chromebooks and have chromebooks ready the first day of school.

Any questions, please email Mr. Romano.

post_text:
New London Schools encourage academic diligence and accountability; therefore, all students will BEGIN the fall season eligible, but it will be up to the individual student to maintain his or her academic eligibility by meeting New London‚Äôs normal 1.7 GPA requirement at grade check points every 3 weeks throughout the first grading period.

Any student failing to meet the 1.7 GPA requirement at a designated grade check will be declared immediately ineligible for competition through the next grade check. Students will be allowed to continue practicing with the team/group they are a member of, but prohibited from dressing for or traveling to competition until they complete a successful grade check.

Grade checks will be completed by the athletic director by 10:00 a.m. on the following dates:
September 18th
October 9th
October 30th - End of the quarter

Fall coaches have been updated with the current GPA‚Äôs for their athletes, and many have already been working on plans to encourage both athletic and academic success for our student athletes.

The COVID 19 situation is definitely uncharted territory, and as we ease back into athletics, we are taking an abundance of caution to protect the health and safety of our athletes and coaching staff. The Ohio High School Athletic Association (OHSAA), Governor DeWine, and our own Huron County Health Department have all given mandatory regulations, guidelines, and best practices with one goal in mind: a safe return to sports and activities for all of our students.

The most recent best practice being implemented is regarding travel outside the state of Ohio. Please understand that due to the spike in COVID 19 cases in popular vacation spots, students and coaches will be‚Ä¶

Class of 2020 Graduation UpDate
**Please share this information**

Good afternoon,
We received approval of a revised graduation plan yesterday that will allow us to give speeches live, as well as, be out of our vehicles more during our graduation ceremony. I have attached the plan approved by the Huron County Health Department. This plan meets the three priorities set by our senior class officers:

#1 We graduate together
#2 We walk the stage
#3 We graduate at the school

This plan also meets the goal to maintain as many aspects of a traditional commencement ceremony as possible. Emails have been sent to student accounts and parents. If you have any questions, please feel free to contact me directly.

eyetter@newlondonschools.k12.oh.us

post_text: While we are excited that our student athletes and coaches are allowed to get started with their summer training/skills programs, this news came as a surprise to us. As a school district we need to make sure that our facilities, both indoor and outdoors, are ready to meet the guidelines provided by the Ohio Dept. of Health and the OHSAA. For that reason, we will delay the start of any program. The health and safety of our student athletes and coaching staff must remain at the center of any reopening of our athletic facilities.
text: While we are excited that our student athletes and coaches are allowed to get started with their summer training/skills programs, this news came as a surprise to us. As a school district we need to make sure that our facilities, both indoor and outdoors, are ready to meet the guidelines provided by the Ohio Dept. of Health and the OHSAA. For that reason, we will delay the start of any program. The health and safety of our student athletes and coaching staff must remain at the center of any reopening of our athletic facilities.

post_text:
Spring Sport Uniform Turn In:

On Wednesday May 13, 2020 we will have uniform turn in for spring sport athletes. Coaches will be at the school to collect uniforms from 6:00-6:45 pm. There will be designated spots for each spring sport.

Track Coaches will be collecting uniforms at the high school entrance doors. The track coaches will be outside the doors for uniform turn in. This is for High School and Middle School track athletes.

Softball Coaches will be collecting uniforms by the bell going into the event entrance doors. This uniform turn in is for JV and Varsity players. Coach Hazen and Coach Campbell will be at the bell collecting uniforms.

Baseball Coaches will be collecting uniforms at the locker room entrance. Coach Gentry and his coaching staff will be outside to collect uniforms. This uniform turn in is for JV and Varsity players.

Uniforms are to be turned in and athletes will leave after they turn in uniforms. Social Distancing protocol will be followed at all times.

All athletes must stay in their vehicle when they turn in uniforms.

post_text:
New London Schools will be honoring our graduating seniors on the evening of May 20th with a #BeTheLight event. Seniors are invited to line Wildcat Drive at 8:00pm (parade start time) along with the New London's local Safety Services and First Responders. The parade will leave the North end of Wildcat drive onto East Street and continue to SR 162 headed toward downtown. Our seniors will turn south on SR 60 to Grove Street to get to the Park.
At 8:20 the stadium will be lit for 20 minutes and 20 seconds. All participants and spectators are reminded to maintain the appropriate social distancing and remain in their vehicles throughout the parade and stadium event.

Extended School Closure Tech Support

If you are having technology issues during the extended school closure, you may use the call-in tech support line, (234) 231-0461, to have devices remotely assessed. A parent/guardian must be present to receive call-in services.

The following technical issues are examples of how call-in tech support can assist:
Password resets for Google or Chromebook
Account creations for Google or Chromebook
Computer issues while you are logged in
File issues
Web browser issues
Devices not working properly

The technology department will be available at the Elementary Main Entrance, BY APPOINTMENT ONLY, Tuesdays and Thursdays from 9:00am-10:45am for device pickup and 11:00am-1:00pm for device dropoff.

Fisher-Titus
April 1 at 10:00 PM ¬∑

Our community has once again stepped up to provide assistance as we face this COVID-19 pandemic. In just a week‚Äôs time, several area schools, businesses, and individuals used their 3D printing resources to make around 800 plastic headbands for face shields for our front line staff. The face shield used in addition to a mask protects our front line workers. This allows the actual face mask to be used longer, preserving personal protective equipment (PPE). Since the headbands are plastic, they can be sterilized and reused without fear of contamination. You can see them in this picture as two of our respiratory therapists participate in COVID-19 education with a manikin.

A special thank you to ‚Ä¶

Are you spending more time at home and looking for something to do? Do you have little ones at home looking to be creative? Participate in FTMC's Community Art Drive!

FTMC has received several questions on how the community can show their appreciation for our local health care heroes or cheer up patients and residents at Fisher-Titus Medical Center, Norwalk Memorial Home, and the Carriage House. In order to minimize contact and practice social distancing, we‚Äôre excited to be doing a virtual art drive. Creations can be sent to ArtDrive@ftmc.com and they will be printed and displayed in various locations at Fisher-Titus. Some ideas to get you started are:
‚óä Sidewalk chalk drawings

‚óä Uplifting cards

‚óä Window displays

Pose for a photo with your art or snap a photo of your creation on its own. We can‚Äôt wait to see what you come up with and we are so grateful for the support our community has shown us these last few weeks! Thank you!

post_text:
A message from Superintendent Brad Romano:

This message is specifically for the class of 2020 and their families. Due to the extension of our school closure through May 1, 2020, the decision has been made to postpone our Senior Scholarship and Awards Night originally scheduled for May 20th. Additionally, scholarship applications that were originally due on Monday April 6th will now be due on Wednesday April 15. All scholarship applications are available on our district website. Submission of scholarship applications must be emailed to Ms. Rhonda by the 15th. Please do not submit any paper copies to us this time. Additional information regarding our postponed scholarship night will be made available once there is more clarity to our return to the building. As always, stay safe Wildcats!

post_text:
YEARBOOK NEWS!

Wondering how to order a 2020 middle school or high school yearbook? All sales are online. Go to www.balfour.com to purchase either book. Sales end May 22. Only a limited amount of extras will be printed, so make sure you buy your's this spring. Books should still be delivered by the end of August. The staff has been working everyday from home to make this a once-in-a-lifetime, historic book! We thank you for your support!

Attention Parents of the Class of 2020,
In light of the disruption to our school year, the Wildcat Yearbook Staff is offering FREE senior shout-outs. These are brief messages, written by parents, to their graduating seniors, that will then be published in the 2020 yearbook. If you are interested, please email Mrs. Ebinger mebinger@newlondon.k12.oh.us a message of 140 characters or less, along with one photo. These are due no later than Friday, April 10.

post_text: I want to remind families that we are currently registering students for our grab and go meal program. This program is for all children under the age of 18 that reside in our district, including home schooled students, students that open enroll out of the district, and our NL students that attend EHOVE. We do not want any child to go hungry during this time. While the district works out the logistics of the program and works with the ODE for the proper licensure, I want to inform families that the Alliance Church is helping to fill in until our program starts. Families can contact Buddy Workman or the Church office for details. Mr. Workman‚Äôs phone number is 419-631-0683 and the Church Office phone number is 419-929-8133.

post_text:
Parents,
Earlier today I emailed a survey/registration to district parents for our Grab & Go Meal Program. This was to help us gauge a need and order enough supplies get started. I want to share the additional news that our application through the State, although not approved, is receiving positive feedback which will allow us to offer our meals free to all school age children.

Additionally, the last thing I want is for a child to go hungry during this global pandemic. After talking with Samantha Matthews, our Cafeteria Supervisor, we would like to extend our Grab n Go Meal Program to those district residents that open enroll their students to other schools districts or attend private parochial schools. Now is the time to come together and support each other. If any family has need, please complete this registration form and we will contact you and provide specific information once our program begins. If there are any questions please email me at bromano@nlschools.org or bromano@newlondon.k12.oh.us
Thank you

post_text:
A message from Superintendent Brad Romano:
Dear Wildcat Families:
The flu season is always a challenging time for our schools and this year is no different with the news of the coronavirus. Since all of the schools in the area could be affected, the superintendents throughout Huron county felt it important to communicate as one regarding what we are all doing on this effort. That starts with this letter.
Of immediate importance, please know that there are zero reports of the virus in any of the schools in Huron County. A message from Superintendent Brad Romano:
Dear Wildcat Families:
The flu season is always a challenging time for our schools and this year is no different with the news of the coronavirus. Since all of the schools in the area could be affected, the superintendents throughout Huron county felt it important to communicate as one regarding what we are all doing on this effort. That starts with this letter.
Of immediate importance, please know that there are zero reports of the virus in any of the schools in Huron County. A message from NLLS Superintendent Brad Romano:

Good morning, I‚Äôd like to provide an update regarding today‚Äôs school closure. For starters, I‚Äôd like to thank Chief Marco and the NLPD for their quick and extensive investigation into this matter. Those responsible for the social media postings are in custody. Based on the outcome of their investigation, we are 100% confident that our students, staff, and school facility are completely safe and classes will resume tomorrow morning for all students. I appreciate the patience and understanding of our community during this incident. In situations such as this I firmly believe that we cannot exercise too much caution and want to thank everyone for their support.

I appreciate that there are many questions in situations like this. At this time it is a police matter and the school is not able to provide details or specifics. If you have specific questions, would encourage you to contact the local police department.

post_text:
A message from Superintendent Brad Romano:
This evening we became aware of a threat on social media towards our school district. Through collaboration with our partners at NLPD, the decision has been made to close school for Wednesday, February 19, 2020, allowing law enforcement to complete their investigation. I am sure you can understand the need for an abundance of caution in this matter as we work to ensure the safety of our students, staff, and overall school community. I will provide updates tomorrow when they are available. Thank you
